1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,498
The Sharpe Ratio is the single most cited performance metric

2
00:00:04,598 --> 00:00:09,404
in finance. It's on every fund factsheet, every backtest report,

3
00:00:09,504 --> 00:00:13,543
every quant resume. And it has a fundamental flaw that

4
00:00:13,643 --> 00:00:18,142
can make a catastrophically risky strategy look like a safe,

5
00:00:18,242 --> 00:00:22,817
consistent winner. Today I'll show you exactly what that flaw

6
00:00:22,917 --> 00:00:26,420
is, and the fix that professionals use instead.

7
00:00:28,320 --> 00:00:34,418
Welcome to QuantiFire. Both the Sharpe and Sortino ratios measure risk-adjusted

8
00:00:34,518 --> 00:00:38,733
return — how much return are you generating per unit of

9
00:00:38,833 --> 00:00:43,284
risk taken. But they disagree on what counts as risk. That

10
00:00:43,384 --> 00:00:49,796
disagreement matters enormously when your return distribution is asymmetric — which

11
00:00:49,896 --> 00:00:53,876
in DeFi and systematic trading, it almost always is.

12
00:00:55,476 --> 00:01:00,504
The Sharpe Ratio: your average excess return above the risk-free

13
00:01:00,604 --> 00:01:05,312
rate, divided by the standard deviation of all your returns.

14
00:01:05,409 --> 00:01:08,018
The numerator — shown in teal — is

15
00:01:08,118 --> 00:01:11,525
your excess return above the risk-free rate.

16
00:01:11,609 --> 00:01:16,451
The denominator — shown in red — is the standard deviation of

17
00:01:16,551 --> 00:01:21,556
ALL returns, up AND down. A month where you made eight percent?

18
00:01:21,656 --> 00:01:26,417
That goes in. A month where you lost four percent? That also

19
00:01:26,517 --> 00:01:32,413
goes in. The Sharpe treats both identically as volatility to be penalized.

20
00:01:33,476 --> 00:01:38,375
Here is the flaw made concrete. Strategy A returns a flat

21
00:01:38,475 --> 00:01:43,288
two percent every single month — no drama, no variation.

22
00:01:43,342 --> 00:01:48,575
Strategy B averages the same two percent but with volatile swings:

23
00:01:48,675 --> 00:01:52,938
some months of plus eight percent, some of minus four.

24
00:01:53,009 --> 00:01:58,957
Both strategies have nearly identical Sharpe Ratios. But a rational investor

25
00:01:59,057 --> 00:02:03,971
prefers Strategy B — those plus eight percent months are gains,

26
00:02:04,071 --> 00:02:08,269
not risk. The Sharpe Ratio cannot tell the difference.

27
00:02:09,342 --> 00:02:14,746
The Sortino Ratio fixes this. The denominator uses only downside

28
00:02:14,846 --> 00:02:19,992
deviation — the standard deviation of returns that fall below

29
00:02:20,092 --> 00:02:24,722
a target threshold, usually zero or the risk-free rate.

30
00:02:24,809 --> 00:02:30,387
Returns above the threshold — shown in teal — are completely ignored

31
00:02:30,487 --> 00:02:35,146
in the denominator. Returns below it — shown in red — are

32
00:02:35,246 --> 00:02:40,741
the only ones penalized. You are penalized only for bad volatility.

33
00:02:40,809 --> 00:02:47,135
Concretely: a strategy with fifteen percent upside deviation and five percent

34
00:02:47,235 --> 00:02:53,226
downside deviation. Sharpe uses a combined sigma of about eleven percent.

35
00:02:53,326 --> 00:02:58,901
Sortino uses only five. Same strategy — radically different scores —

36
00:02:59,001 --> 00:03:02,573
and the Sortino tells the more honest story.

37
00:03:03,609 --> 00:03:08,387
Use the Sharpe Ratio when return distributions are approximately

38
00:03:08,487 --> 00:03:13,646
symmetric and normal — classical equity long-only, diversified factor

39
00:03:13,746 --> 00:03:18,677
portfolios where upside and downside volatility are roughly equal.

40
00:03:18,742 --> 00:03:24,163
Use the Sortino when strategies have skewed distributions — options

41
00:03:24,263 --> 00:03:29,437
writing, trend following, yield farming — any strategy where you

42
00:03:29,537 --> 00:03:33,474
care about the asymmetry between wins and losses.

43
00:03:33,542 --> 00:03:37,248
And use the Calmar Ratio when you care specifically

44
00:03:37,348 --> 00:03:41,204
about maximum drawdown — the preferred metric for CTA

45
00:03:41,304 --> 00:03:45,010
traders who manage to explicit drawdown thresholds.

46
00:03:46,076 --> 00:03:51,404
Now the most important warning. Some strategies manufacture high Sharpe

47
00:03:51,504 --> 00:03:56,603
Ratios by selling tail risk — consistently collecting small premiums

48
00:03:56,703 --> 00:04:00,808
from selling naked puts or short volatility strategies.

49
00:04:00,876 --> 00:04:04,960
This produces a smooth return series right up until

50
00:04:05,060 --> 00:04:09,227
a volatility spike wipes them out. Watch this equity

51
00:04:09,327 --> 00:04:13,904
curve: beautiful, steady growth, Sharpe of two point one.

52
00:04:14,009 --> 00:04:17,659
Then a sudden cliff. The Sharpe looked great the

53
00:04:17,759 --> 00:04:20,941
whole time. This is the Sharpe Ratio trap.

54
00:04:21,009 --> 00:04:26,781
Always pair Sharpe with tail metrics: maximum drawdown,

55
00:04:26,881 --> 00:04:32,333
CVaR at ninety-five percent, skewness, and kurtosis.

56
00:04:33,409 --> 00:04:40,078
For DeFi specifically: liquidity provision strategies have asymmetric profiles

57
00:04:40,178 --> 00:04:45,631
— gradual impermanent loss accumulation punctuated by fee income

58
00:04:45,731 --> 00:04:50,925
creates a right-skewed return distribution. Use Sortino here.

59
00:04:51,009 --> 00:04:57,267
Funding rate arbitrage has near-normally distributed daily returns with rare

60
00:04:57,367 --> 00:05:02,789
positive funding spike events. Sharpe works there, but always pair

61
00:05:02,889 --> 00:05:05,885
it with CVaR to catch the spike risk.

62
00:05:06,942 --> 00:05:11,921
Never evaluate a strategy with a single metric. If the Sortino

63
00:05:12,021 --> 00:05:17,738
is significantly higher than the Sharpe, the strategy has positive skew

64
00:05:17,838 --> 00:05:21,506
— a fat right tail — that's usually good news.

65
00:05:21,542 --> 00:05:24,451
If they are roughly equal, the distribution

66
00:05:24,551 --> 00:05:27,250
is near-symmetric and the metrics agree.

67
00:05:27,342 --> 00:05:33,016
If the Sortino is lower than the Sharpe, the strategy has negative skew

68
00:05:33,116 --> 00:05:38,546
— hidden tail risk lurking below the surface. That is your red flag.

69
00:05:38,609 --> 00:05:43,944
Minimum reporting standard: Sharpe, Sortino, Max Drawdown,

70
00:05:44,044 --> 00:05:47,317
and Skewness. Never just one number.

71
00:05:47,409 --> 00:05:50,748
Next up: Value at Risk — how do quants put

72
00:05:50,848 --> 00:05:55,334
an actual dollar figure on the worst-case loss? It's the

73
00:05:55,434 --> 00:06:00,984
number regulators require, and it has some nasty surprises. Subscribe

74
00:06:01,084 --> 00:06:04,997
and I'll see you in the next episode. QuantiFire.

